WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.584
Welcome to this module on choosing the right solar panel.

00:00:06.584 --> 00:00:23.680
You'll learn to identify the parts of a module, read its specifications, tell the three panel types apart, and recommend the right panel for a site.

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:30.560
A single cell makes only about half a volt.

00:00:30.560 --> 00:00:40.320
Wire many cells together and seal them, and you get a module.

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:47.680
Connect modules together and you get an array.

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:55.251
A module is a sealed sandwich built to last 25 years.

00:00:55.251 --> 00:01:13.680
Tempered glass on top, cells sealed between two layers of EVA, a weatherproof back-sheet, an aluminium frame, and a junction box.

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:20.860
Monocrystalline is black and the most efficient.

00:01:20.860 --> 00:01:28.189
Polycrystalline is blue and easier on the budget.

00:01:28.189 --> 00:01:35.818
Thin-film is flexible and the calmest in high heat.

00:01:35.818 --> 00:01:40.006
The site decides the choice.

00:01:40.006 --> 00:01:45.1000
Watt-peak is measured at standard test conditions.

00:01:45.1000 --> 00:02:03.622
Voc is the open-circuit voltage, Isc the short-circuit current, and the temperature coefficient shows how much power is lost as the panel heats up.

00:02:03.622 --> 00:02:22.822
In the 3D lab you can rotate the module, explode its layers, switch between the three technologies, and change the sunlight and temperature to watch the live power output respond.

00:02:22.822 --> 00:02:39.001
You can now name the layers of a solar module, read its key specifications, tell the three technologies apart, and choose the right panel for a site.

00:02:39.001 --> 00:02:42.150
That's the installer's craft.
